,Recommended,249990,12706533,"Posted: 31 October, 2014",all,naali,"If you are looking for a couch coop game, this one is the best or one of the best.Levels include increasingly challenging puzzle and hack n slash level. Some levels are almost purely slow puzzly levels, some are fast paced fighting levels and rest are some combination of those two.Game mechanics are simple and are introduced sufficiently smoothly so you don't feel overwhelmed. Later on these mechanics are combined in various ways and the game never feels boring.Biggest con for this game would be that its not a single-player game. You can play it alone but its not even half the fun.So if you are looking for a coop game to have fun with your friends this game is for you."
,Recommended,249990,13974704,"Posted: 13 January, 2015",all,Swongstrong,"Edit #1: This game is pretty hard.  When I play this, I get quite frustrated, but I like a good challenge.Some of the challenges seem impossible, but it might just be because I'm a newb.In this game, each ""level"" is referred to as a trial.Each trial has 3 achievements you can unlock:-Completing the Level-A unique level challenge (such as beating a level without killing monster spawn points, etc.)-And beating the level with a speed run aspect to it (Time Trials).When you beat a trial, you earn ""crystals"" which are basically level ups for your gladiator.Crystals unlock active and passive skills to make your hero stronger.There are 4 Heroes (weapons), you can choose from, and that you can change at any point in the game:-Volcanic Hammer (Warrior class)-Spirit Claws (Rogue class)-Ice Shield (Paladin class)-Storm Bow (Hunter class)It plays like an arcade game, but man, it is pretty hard, and my frustration is a 9/10 most of the time. lolThe cool thing with this game, is that the puzzles and monster spawns scale with the number of players in a game.So the more players, the harder the game is!For completionists, the good thing is that you can compare your rankings with other players from around the globe to see how well (or poorly) you've done.All in all, a good game, and would recommend even at full price. :)[END OF EDIT]~~~~~~~~~~So far so good!I've been eyeing this game for quite some time now, and have passed up various Steam sales, either out of forgetfulness or laziness.66% Off, 50% Off, I finally picked this game up for $2.24 (85% Off), and the initial game play is decent so far.Initially, the game has a Gauntlet Legends/Warcraft 3: Custom Map/Use Map Settings vibe to it.The game plays similar to StarCraft 2 Challenges, mixed with some Gauntlet Legends-Arcade style vibe to it.I've read the reviews prior to mine where the difficulty ramps up as the game progresses, and isn't fair towards the later stages of the game... (Dungeon Defenders suffers from that, where you HAVE to play with people)I haven't gotten that far yet, however, when I get to that point, I'll be able to update this review and give my whole-hearted opinion of the game.There is one thing though: the story/voice acting, albeit, is minimal thus far, is very lacking/dry. (Supposedly the game was created with a team of 7, so it's just a side thought.  You aren't playing the game for voice acting, you're playing it for the fun factor!)All in all, the Trials are challenging... it gets me frustrated trying to race the clock and I get killed in the process. lol.I promise to update this review as I progress in the game. :)"
,Recommended,249990,33054700,Posted: 30 June,all,scathelock,"What separates a cheap gimmick from a solid game mechanic is that a gimmick is a cute trick that's shown once, easily implemented, and then forgotten about. In ""Forced"", you're introduced to a variety of simple mechanics - but after learning them, you actually have to plan out your approach, and then you have to execute those mechanics under evolving conditions.As a gladiator, you can equip one of four weapons, all of which are made available to you at the start and can be swapped out whenever you're not in a combat arena. What's impressive is that each one feels distinctly unique yet  equally effective. There is no ""right"" answer, but you need to familiarize yourself with whatever skillset you choose. Want to detonate kamikaze creeps at a distance with the Bow and Arrow? You'll have to position yourself so your line of sight isn't blocked by other enemies or obstacles. Or would you rather stand fast and absorb their explosions with the Shield? You'll need to make sure that your Blocking ability hasn't been triggered by other creeps by the time they connect. Or would you prefer setting them off with the invincibility frame of the Dagger's dash? You'd best double-check that you aren't dashing into an even worse position. ""Forced"" also uses my favorite kind of customization system, the kind that rewards good performance and encourages experimentation: outside of combat, you're free to mix and match any three active and three passive abilities that you've unlocked. This isn't a game for grinding - if you want to mindlessly farm loot for better gear and levels, search elsewhere. ""Forced"" is looking for players to go in, die, figure out what else they could try or how they could better execute their plan, and then go in again.And on that note, you will definitely die, frequently with a curse on your lips. You will curse the fixed camera angle. You will curse the melee aiming controls. You will curse the occasionally dodgy hitbox. And then you'll put all of that aside and stubbornly head back into the same arena, and tackle the same enemies with a bit more insight and a touch more finesse, and then, suddenly, you'll have completed the Challenge and beaten the Time Limit and shout in triumph as you finally relax and soak in the feeling of a victory well earned.The majority of my game time has been spent playing solo, which can be satisfying if you're the masochistic type; the game definitely wants to be played with friends. The framing device is another nice little touch. While it's nothing deep - just some light set dressing - the setting is plausible and manages to set itself apart from the typical ""heroic journey to kill the ancient evil and seize forbidden treasure"" cliche. Each of the major bosses has enough style to differentiate himself from the others, and Balfus has enough dialogue variety that he never becomes an annoyance.""Forced"" is by no means a perfect game (refer to the aforementioned sources of cursing) but it definitely carves out a memorable niche for itself. This is the proving grounds for gamers to test their timing, planning and patience. If you're the sort who's willing to go after tricky challenge objectives and you feel like beating down a small horde of monsters along the way, then grab some buddies and arm up: this arena could take a while."
76561198084000741,Not Recommended,249990,14199399,"Posted: 27 January, 2015",all,ripper,"The game is quite different from what I expected when I was buying it. It's not that much about puzzles or real combat skills (I imagined something like dodging at the right time, using different attacks per enemy weaknesses, combo-ing, etc). No, it's more about great cooperation between players (voice chat is an absolute must), selecting correct skills from the skill tree for that particular level, and, unfortunately, also about grinding. The game is quite hard, don't expect a casual multiplayer co-op game. You'll need to repeat every level many times to at least finish it. And then, you'll need to repeat it many times more in order to fulfill the challenge or time criteria. If you don't do it, you'll be very much underpowered in the later levels and the difficulty will go from high to insane.So, the principle of the game is not to enjoy many different levels. The number or levels is quite low (25). The principle of the game is to rinse and repeat until you finish themperfectly. It's not what I expected and it's not what I enjoy, but tastes differ, I'm sure many people will like it. That's not why I'm giving it a thumbs down.The thumbs down goes for technical execution. From technical level, this game is horrible. Network issues are extremely common - the game splits and people see different things on their screens, someone can't move at all, someone dies but gets stuck in the dying animation and glitches the level, unable to complete it, and the list goes on. But, that's not the worst thing. The worst thing is thecamera. It deserves a paragraph on its own.The camera. The devs had an idea that you need to see all characters at the same time, all the time. So if you go into different directions, the camera zooms out to make sure you see all characters. Questionably a good idea, with the worst implementation ever. First, this camera mode is mandatory, you can't switch between ""focused camera"" (seeing just yourself in the center of the screen) and ""overview camera"" (seeing everyone). No, it's just the overview camera. So, if you go far apart (necessary in some levels), you're zoomed out immensely, and your characters (and enemies) are very small. Try to use your skills effectively then! You're also in a corner or near the edge of the screen, so you have no idea what's near you in certain directions. The camera constantly shifts (as others move around), which throws your aim out of balance (especially frustration when playing the archer character). And to top all of that, the devs even botched it so much, that very often the camera actually crops your character and you're behind the edge or the corner of the screen! So, you don't actually see yourself, or the enemies around you, and you're expected to fight them and survive. Please don't forget this game is extremely punishing for even the smallest errors. You'll cry, you'll shout, you'll tear things apart. That's how bad the camera is.One final note, this game has to be played with a stable group of friends. No one might be missing any time. The reason is that every time you start a game, you'll only receive those gems, which have been completed by *all* members of the party. So if one of your friends was not available last time, you'll need to repeat all levels with him/her again, and complete all of it again. This was not the best design choice, and again, you have no option to configure this, you need to live with it. Consider it, if you don't have a stable group of friends to play and finish this game with.So, to sum it up, the game mechanics are not necessarily bad, they can be even enjoyable. But the technical execution is definitely a reason to avoid this game. And that's 18 months after release, so there's no hope of having it improved, ever."
