76561197979643793,Not Recommended,249990,11865299,"Posted: 25 August, 2014",all,RustyRaven,"I really hate having to recommend against getting this game. I really wanted to like it but the experience the game gave just declined over the course of 14 hours. Let's start from the beginning.I bought this game pretty much right after it came out in 2013 and played it with 2 other friends. The net-code was unstable at launch which made it extremely difficult to get online co-op games (one of the main selling points) to work. When it did work though it was great entertainment. However, an unstable multiplayer was not the only mechanical issue I ran into and I crashed several times. Add numerous bugs and you have a less than stellar experience. A year later I picked up the game to finish it and while the net-code has gotten better it's still wonky and there are still bugs throughout, in fact the last boss fight of the game was more or less ruined as the big bad evil guy crapped out on me and was stuck in his walking cycle unnable to attack.Even with those mechanical flaws I still managed to have a good time but at the halfway mark of the game things just go down hill. See the game is structured a lot like an old Crash Bandicoot game (the second one to be exact). The game is split into worlds that has a series of levels along with a boss fight. Every level has 3 crystals to obtain. The first is obtained by simply beating the level, the second by completing a challenge tied to the level and finally a crystal based on completion time.The structure works really well and here's why: The game is a mix of RPG, Hack 'N' Slash and light Puzzle elements. Your character has active abilities, passive abilities and a special ability tied to each of the 4 classes (Hammer charges over time, bow can be charged manually, shield blocks etc.). However, in order gain new abilities you need to get crystals by beating levels. This creates a very real incentive to complete levels several times to pick up all the crystals.This brings us to the levels themselves and the puzzle element. Throughout the game you'll be escorted by Balfus a flying orb that might as well have been called Navi. Balfus has a lot of quips throughout the game and he happily chats away whenever he's given the chance and becomes real grating, real fast. Especially when constantly replaying levels to get those final crystals. Now the levels are structured so that you need Balfus to activate several items and objects by making him fly into them and for the first half of the game it's great fun to play with all the different objects in the world and there are some really creative puzzles in there. Like I said though, at the half way point it seriously starts to feel like you're simply going through the motions and things become repetitive just like Balfus' endlessly repeating lines.Another few gripes I feel deserve mentioning are the bosses whom have way to much health for their own good, seriously they are ♥♥♥♥ing sponges soaking damage like high-end kleenexes. The mark system which adds extra damage from abilities and basic attacks don't do enough to quickly wear down bosses at a reasonable rate and the boss levels which are supposed to be epic become tedious. The fact that the invisible creatures can only be spotted by Balfus and the fact there's only one Balfus and most likely more than one player it is aggrivating to kill just one, especially when they have enough health to soak several fully marked abilities. I could go on but I think I've made my point.In conclusion, I feel really bad for not recommending the game because I know this is the first game by the dev team and I know they worked really hard on it, but it just lacks polish and the player-experience is not optimal as a result. If you really want to play this game, get it on sale."
76561197973957094,Not Recommended,249990,11888477,"Posted: 27 August, 2014",all,[2FN] Solrentei,"If you want a good coop game then look elsewhere!Where to start? Want deep character customization? Too bad! Pick between four set characters (if a buddy grabs your favorite character, you have to play as a different one) with only one weapon set per character. while you can certainly upgrade their abilities and switch between a few special powers per character, its hardly in depth enough to make you feel like you have the ability to make important changes to your character to augment to your own playing style. And with zero loot in the game you aren't allowed to even optimize your character's gear in any way.Howabout the maps? Well, don't play this game expecting long sprawling dungeons, each level is more of a small arena with waves of enemies and little puzzles to solve. And when I mean arena I literally mean a smallish circular map where enemies will run in from doorways on the outside as well as from a few spawners. Its been extremely difficult to connect with friends, but when working the teamwork required to get through these levels is simple, but enjoyable enough (though it is a simple button masher) when played in coop, however that leads me to the greatest problem of this game in my opinion:When playing coop with friends with each of you on DIFFERENT computers, you are still forced to share the camera as if playing a couch coop with your buddies on the same screen. This can lead to anything from mild annoyance to intense frustration while playing. I can think of nothing more frustrating while trying to play this game then when my character is pushed off the screen because my friends are on the other side of the screen, and I am now forced to fight blindly or ask my friends to stop what they're doing and come back to my side of the arena. This problem might not be as frustrating when played with just 1-2 other friends, but if you get a full group of four together you'll run into this problem often. Its possible this has been fixed, though the fact that you were ever forced (no pun intended) to play this way in the first place is ridiculous!In terms of replayability, there is no randomness to this game, or any abundance of places you might of missed to explore. The game's main sense of replayability comes in the fact that each arena playthrough is timed, and ranked among others. The incentive being to replay the arena to try and get a better score.There's a reason why most of the people reviewing this game don't make it past twenty hours of game time... However, that being said, if this sounds like the type of game you want to play then by all means give it a whirl. Just don't be fooled into thinking that this game will be at all like an in depth rpg dungeon crawler. If you're looking for that type of game look elsewhere."
