,Recommended,249990,7781270,"Posted: 26 November, 2013",all,okram2k,"Newly released on steam is a new indy action rpg game called Forced. It’s available for $14.99 and caught my eye. If you have not already seen it, check out the story of BetaDwarf. The makers of the game living together on a shoe string budget for the last few years (even eating together to save money) in order to fulfill their dreams is probably reason enough to plop down $15 on the game but luckily there’s more than just that to give it a try.Forced puts you in the role of a gladiator, who’s tribe is more or less only in existence to breed warriors who take on deadly challenges for the enjoyment of others. Now that you’re old enough to fight or whatnot you are sent into the halls of trials to await your destiny. Which is probably going to involve you being killed almost immediately. After a basic tutorial the game opens up into a series of challenges you can run each in growing complexity and difficulty. You have four classes of gear to chose from and the more challenges you complete the more skill points you unlock to become more and more powerful.As you get yourself into the game you will notice quite quickly, this game is HARD. But it’s not hard in a cheap OMG WHAT WAS THAT ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥T!?!? sort of way. No it’s hard because it is unforgivably difficult. The game doesn’t hold any punches and it hits you hard from early on and never lets up. You know how there are those crazy people who are addicted to spicy foods and must find the absolutely most spicy thing around? (Usually because they are addicted to endorphins) Well this game is like eating the spiciest of peppers with no milk to wash it down with. To a lot of us we’ll spit it out, frustrated by the game’s infuriating difficulty but there are some who will absolutely love it.Here’s the thing, with easy games you get less triumph from your successes. Sure they might give you a constant supply of ‘oh nice’ over and over again but eventually it doesn’t really feel like much accomplishment. Forced on the other hand is so brutally difficult that after failure after failure after failure when you finally succeed oh it feels so succulent, so sweet, so amazing. The game manages to walk a very fine line of being so difficult that success is amazingly rare while also giving you just enough hope that you might possibly figure out how to succeed, just maybe.One of the things I really like about Forced is the way they handle character progression. Yes there are four distinct classes to play but you can switch freely between them before each challenge. Also you can pick your skills freely each challenge as well. This makes choosing the class and what skills vitally important before each challenge as some are better at certain things than others. It’s also important to get familiar with each class as opposed to only playing one as you might be unnecessarily handicapping yourself in a challenge. The classes are fairly unique with a defender, a ranger, a brute heavy melee, and a faster more finesse melee. Each have their own weakness and strengths and if you are struggling with a challenge it might be time to switch up the classes or skill load out.Each challenge has three crystals (or skill points, really) available to be earned. The first is earned by simply defeating the challenge. A second is offered for doing some sort of optional skill mission and a third for completing the challenge in a certain amount of time. The more crystals you unlock the stronger your character gets, which should, in theory, make it easier to do more challenges. I like the skill system with active and passive abilities to chose from and having more options unlocked as you acquire more crystals. You are also able to have more skills active the as you go along, greatly increasing your character’s potency. Combat is also fairly smooth. Your character moves independently of the direction you’re aiming and combat uses a ‘mark’ gimmick. Each time you hit an enemy with your normal attack increases the effect of your special attack up to five times. So it’s best to prep enemies with normal attacks then hit them with specials, rinse and repeat. It’s fairly straight forward and works pretty well while adding extra tension as you try to get five marks on a big baddy before you unleash your awesome special attack.Now Forced is not without its flaws. I imagine the game would be really fun to play online (or really frustrating depending on who you play with.) But alas after trying a few times I was unable to connect to a game. I suspect the issue is probably with my firewall or something but just frustrating when internet connectivity gets in the way (seriously, why can’t online games just *work* these days?) Also if you change the controls the menus and options don’t update to match your custom control scheme which can get a wee bit annoying when trying to navigate menus or load out your skills. Also I’m not sure if it’s a big complaint or not but there is no loot in the game as the only rewards you get for completing quests are skill unlocking crystals. This can add even more frustration when you’re trying to unlock extra crystals and are unable to beat a challenge fast enough. I guess it is just how I am but darn-it I like loot!The game certainly looks a lot better than most indy games I’ve played recently. And everything is fairly smoothed and well polished. The challenges offer a fairly good variety and do a great job of mixing combat and puzzles. I can tell that the developers have put their heart and soul into the product and even though it is probably too difficult for me I can still appreciate their work. And it just feels so good to finally get a victory on a challenge that kicked my♥♥♥♥♥five times in a row! If you love a good challenge, get this game. If you can’t handle getting frustrated at a game, maybe you should pass.Final Score:Graphics: 8/10Game Play: 8/10Music / Ambiance: 8/10Story: 7/10Value: 9/10Overall: 8/10Read more indy game reviews on my blog!http://markofithian.com"
,Recommended,249990,7487714,"Posted: 26 October, 2013",all,Nàmahs,"Forced is an interesting take on a co-op hack and slash. The foundation of the game  is sort of like Gauntlet, a  top down game where you pick a class and then mow down mobs and move through the battle areana.But, fun as that is, that's not the point of the game. Each level has a puzzle or objective. Some of these are pretty tricky, and not only do you have to figure them out, but then you have to somehow execute that plan while still dealing with the monsters and fire being thrown at you. So, imagine solving group puzzles and tossing balls back and forth, all while trying to survive wave after wave of fairly difficult enemies.In any case this game makes for great co-op play, and while difficulty curve starts out gentle, it gets really high. This isn't a game you can just breeze through without a thought, it's a fun little co-op challenge."
